summary: Clara is rewatching Dear White People and strongly recommends it to Neela.
utt: Hi, what you up to?
Not much, chilling out.
Just rewatching Dear White People on Netflix, love it!😍
Oh yeah, heard of it, but not seen it yet? Any good?
Well, yes! I just said it was, LOL. It's about a fictional Ivy League University and the students in one House of Residence.
Why is it called Dear White People?
That's the name of the radio show the main character, Sam, presents on college radio.
Yeah, but why is it so good?
Well, it's mainly stories from the perspective of black students there, which I find very interesting. The characters are strong and likeable too.
I suppose it's rather different from the UK, then?

It seems so, as there is a lot more racial awareness and discrimination there than here. It all kicks off when there is a Blackface party held by an elite group of white students, which gets out of hand.
How's that?

Well, obviously, the black students try to break it up and there's also an incident where one guy, Reggie, gets a loaded gun pointed at him by a campus policeman after he gets into an argument with a white student. It may be at another party, though, I'm not sure of that.
Oh, that sounds pretty strong stuff. What else happens?

Well, there is a young black guy called Lionel who is coming to terms with being gay and is finding his voice as a journalist. He unearths corruption at the uni and he and Sam also uncover some conspiracy theory stuff about secret societies.
Well, I must say, it does sound good, I'll check it out soon!
Definitely, there is supposed to be a Series 3 coming up next year, really looking forward to it!
Well, thanks Clara, I'm just watching the rest of a movie and I'll try Dear White People.
Don't blame me if you get hooked and stay up till 4!
See ya, love!
Bye!

summary: Beth wants to organize a girls weekend to celebrate her mother's 40th birthday. She also wants to work at Deidre's beauty salon. Deidre offers her a few hours on Saturdays as work experience. They set up for a meeting tomorrow.
utt: Hi Beth, how are you love?
Hi Auntie Deirdre, I'm been meaning to message you, had a favour to ask.
Wondered if you had any thought about your Mum's 40th, we've got to do something special!
How about a girls weekend, just mum, me, you and the girls, Kira will have to come back from Uni, of course.
Sounds fab! Get your thinking cap on, it's only in 6 weeks! Bet she's dreading it, I remember doing that!
Oh yeah, we had a surprise party for you, you nearly had a heart attack!
Well, it was a lovely surprise! Gosh, thats nearly 4 years ago now, time flies! What was the favour, darling?
Oh, it was just that I fancied trying a bit of work experience in the salon, auntie.
Well, I am looking for Saturday girls, are you sure about it? you could do well in the exams and go on to college or 6th form.
I know, but it's not for me, auntie, I am doing all foundation papers and I'm struggling with those.
What about a tutor? Kira could help you in the hols.
Maybe, but I'd like to try working. I'm 16 soon, I'm old enough.
I know. Look, pop in tomorrow after school and we'll have a cuppa and a chat.
Yes, thanks auntie. I'd really like to try the beauty therapy side.
Its not for the squeamish, mind. Massage, pedicures, not to mention waxing!
Oh yes, I was chatting to a friend about it yesterday!
Maxine manages the beauty side, you can meet her tomorrow and we'll see how it goes.
Yes, I'd really like that.

We can try a few hours on a Saturday for a couple of weeks as work experience. I'll give you a tenner or so per session to start off for your lunch, coffee and bus fare etc. If you like, we'll take it from there.
OK, I like the sound of it! See you tomorrow Auntie! Love you!
Bye, lovely girl! Xx

summary: Sandra and Brenda used to work together in the clothes factory 25 years ago. Sandra still lives in Kings Norton. Brenda lives in Stoke now. Her husband Bill died 5 years ago. They will meet in Birmingham for a lunch next Saturday about 11. They want to organize a reunion for the Lister's girls.
utt: Hello, is this Sandra Donovan?
Yes, well that was my maiden name, it's Sandra Taylor now.
It's Brenda Riley, we used to work together in the clothes factory!
Oh my God! Bren! How are you, it must be 25 years!
I'm fine, I live in Stoke now, moved away from Brum in the late 90s.
I still live in Kings Norton, same house, same husband! I've got 4 grandchildren now, ages 2, 4, 9 and 15! How about you?
Unfortunately, my husband Bill died 5 years ago, I have only one grandchild, she's 7, my little angel, she doesn't remember her Gramps.
So sorry, love, I remember your Bill, he had long black hair and massive sideburns, didn't he?
Well, yes, about 45 years ago, he was bald when he passed away. He loved to dance, he did Northern Soul, we both did actually. Went up to Wigan on weekends, happy times!
Oh yes, I remember that craze, bit energetic for me! We liked disco instead! We had some great dinner dances with the factory, do you remember them?
Yes! Us all dressed up with our long dresses and the men with their frilly evening shirts, lovely memories!
Do you still see any of the girls from Lister's?
No, but I heard that Marigold Carter died, very sad.
Hey Bren, I've had a brainwave! How about we organise a reunion for the Lister's girls, look on social media for them?
Actually, I was thinking along those lines! Do you fancy meeting up, just you and me? I can come down to Birmingham anytime.
That would be lovely! Can you manage it next Saturday? We could meet about 11ish and go for lunch and a good old trip down memory lane!
Oh yes! I'd love that! I'll get back to you about train times soon!
Ok! Bye love!

OK.
Hey Noah, the twins will be on their way from Notts tomorrow afternoon and passing Windfield. Is it alright if they pop in and collect the quince?
Absolutely! In fact anyone can come any time and just take them from our terrace. Of course it would be great to see your twins again. Haven't seen them for ages!
Well we don't see that much of them either :( They'll be coming home this weekend only because of Alexa's ceremony.
Notts is 3 hours' drive away so small wonder they don't fancy it so much.
I don't blame them! We're both happy they've been doing fine at college. Everything's absolutely fine. You don't have William at home all that often either, do you?

He gets 5 days at Xmas by way of "family care" and 2 weeks off spread over the whole year but never longer that 5 days. They have a strict regime at the academy. But after all these years we've learned to cope with it. What worries me is that he seems to have no time to even think about getting married and start a family of his own.
The fate of most military I guess. Hugely unfair I'd say. Like being married to your regiment!
That's what it sounds like when he talks about himself! I never hear a girl's name! And when I ask, he gets brusque.
Oh dear! What could it mean?
No, not what you think! We know from Capt. Broomsberg about their common escapades. Plenty of women but only that sort of women. No strings.
I never even imagined he might be gay! Surely not. But there must be sth else.
We think he's just so obsessively career-minded. Nothing else counts for him.
He's always been very strong-willed. And he knows what he wants. Well if I were you I wouldn't worry at all.
You're probably right. But you know I'd love it so much to have plenty of grandchildren around me.
They'll come, don't you worry! Look the twins will contact you about the quince. Alright?
Sure. Thank you Sophie for a nice chat!
Thank you for the quince!

summary: Brett's cousin met his wife while playing a game together. Andrew's favorite game is the Final Fantasy. Brett and John haven't heard about it.

I see. Did you think about IT?

Girl, it's the best place to work in! A lot of my friends started as software testers and they are really satisfied. Good money and no rat race.
Zach, are you crazy? I don't have technical studies.

You don't have to. If you have good analytical skills all you need is some online course - Udemy or something. People change their career after years of employment in totally different business. It's not that difficult, really. You should give it a try. Tech is our future.

If you want, I can talk to my friends and they will give you some advice on how to start, what courses to choose and so on.

summary: Samuel's language is Telugu, which is spoken in south east India. It has nearly 90 million speakers; it's written left to right; it's based on Brahmin script. Teluguland has 23 provinces. It's quite poor. "Anna" means "elder brother" and Thammu or Thammadu - "younger brother". Tim's 55, Samuel's 35.
utt: Are you there, Anna?
I am, but I am not called Anna. It's Tim.
Sorry, brother Tim. Anna is just the word for elder brother in my language.
It's a girl's name here. Doesn't sound very brother-like.
My apologies.
So what is your language?
It is Telugu, brother.
is that spoken in India?
Yes, in South east India. Bangalore and Chennai and other places. Nearly 90 million speakers, brother.
Is it one of those written right to left?
No, it is written left to right. It is based on Brahmin script, our writing. If you trace it back far enough it all comes from the Phoenicians, like English writing the same.
Wow.
So it must be pretty big, then, Teluguland?
It is 23 provinces, Anna. But we are not rich as in the north, so many people here are still working for less than a hundred dollars a whole month.
So what is the word for "younger brother" if "Anna" means "elder brother?"
Thammu or Thammadu. You can call me Thammu. I am younger than you.
how old are you, I would have sid about the same as me in your photo.
How old are you, Anna?
Well there you are you see. I am 35 only. So you are my Anna and I am your Thammadu.
Wow sorry to say it but you do look old for 35:
That is because it is not an easy life when you are not earning much money, Anna. We work very hard and have very little. But still we are thankful for what we do have.

summary: Tim wants to organise a board games night for his colleagues. Joe has some good ideas and tips on where to start.
utt: Hey, you have a few minutes?
Sure, what's up?
I'm thinking about inviting a few people from work over and I kinda thought that maybe some boardgames would be a cool idea.
And I wanted to consult the expert on the matter :)
As you know I'm always happy to share my expertise with anyone willing to listen. You will just need to stop me when I get too wound up :D
Haha :) Ok, So I know you ran the local club - any tips how to organize a newbie gaming evening? And what games to bring?
yeah, sure - just a few general tips :)

Start games before you start drinking :) And don't bring any game that is either over-complicated, requires too much time to explain, or god forbid encourages direct conflict - you know, the plotting-scheming stuff. So no Game of Thrones :)
Or alternatively you can chose some cooperative games - like Arkham Horror, Robinson Crusoe, Pandemic
Got it :D
Also would be great to know what theme they all like - if there is one. And if not then there are some 'vanilla' games - like Codenames or Catan. Any idea what they might be into?
Not really - there are some guys who I know like sci-fi and comic books, but no idea about the girls...
The best way - just talk with them - might be surprised by their tastes and experiences. Maybe some of them are already into gaming? There are nerds in every walk of life :)
Yeah, I know, all too well :)
Anyway, thanks for the tips - co-op games sound like a good idea for a start.
yeah, and then if the idea sticks you can roll out the big guns :)
Will do that :)

We'll have a look at them. Now the BBQ. At the weekend I suppose?

Let me check the calendar. Here's our family planner. A horrible name, isn't it? So this weekend suits us fine. At the next one, on Saturday, Mark has penciled something in but I can't read it. So what about this Saturday?
Perfect. At least we know the weather holds. Shall I do the food and you the drinks?
And I'll get us some dessert as well.

summary: Betty's house has mould due to condensation. Andy will send her a quote for the work needed by Friday.
utt: Hello. I have had a good look and have done some tests on the mould in your spare bedroom upstairs and in the dinign room.
Hello Andy. Thank you for that, what are your thoughts?
I think it is caused by condensation, as most of the moist settles on and around the windows.
Why is that?
Those are the coldest areas and therefore where the moist in the warm air turns into water. On the windows its just water, on the walls the moist will allow mould to grow.
So why is it all over the spare room walls, and all around the dining room? but not in other rooms?
Probably because they have external walls which are cooler than internal walls.
so why only that bedroom and not the other ones?
I guess those rooms are most effected as the spare room is next to the bathroom and the dining room next to the kitchen.
But why isnt there mould on the kitchen and bathroom itself then?

I think that is because the kitchen doesn't have external walls and the bathroom has only one external wall and a fan in it. The difference when i measured it between internal wall and external wall is about 4 degrees.
Does that mean we need new double glazed windows or new wall insulation?
Not necessarily. that would make a little difference but would still leave you with moist air in the house, so it would just settle somewhere else.
So what would you recommend?
I would install a fan system, or PIV system, which would circulate air to dilute and take some moisture out of the air. It would be installed in your loft and be on continuously during day and night.
That sounds good. would that be sufficient?
If you buy a decent size it will be, but you would also need to treat your walls to get rid of the current mould. That will not go away by itself.
OK, is this something your company can help with?
It is indeed, we can repaint as well if you want.
Good point. Could you please send me a detailed quote for the work via email?
Of course, I will have that done by Friday.
That would be great. And again, thanks for today!
No problem, speak soon.
